,Recommended,250560,9830104,"Posted: 15 April, 2014",all,WarriorVet,"Fight the Dragon is, in my opinion, one of the coolest game ideas that I have seen, and for the most part it is executed extremely. I originally bought this game in early access and was able to watch it grow, and grow it did.In FTD you create a character, choosing one of the four classes: Rogue, Fighter, Ice Wizard, or Fire Wizard. The classes themselves each have a unique feel to them and it is fun to check each of them out. There is a decent amount of abilities to choose from for each class and they all seem pretty fun to use. You can customize your character with the in-game models provided or you can download new, unique models from the Steam Workshop.Where the game truly shines is the ACK - Adventure Creation Kit. This allows anyone to use all of the assets in the game to create their own unique levels. Obviously some adventures turn out better than others, but there is a healthy amount of extremely creative individuals making adventures that are truly astounding. You create everything in your adventure from NPCs and their dialogue to the landscape and buildings. The most creative individuals have weaved some of the coolest stories I've seen in their adventures, and when you complete them you can even follow the creator to be updated whenever they create a new adventure. There are also measures to prevent creators from making adventures that just give you massive amounts of gear or treasure without doing anything, which is a good thing (why exploit a game, the point is to play and have fun)! Writing about it simply doesn't do it justice and it must be seen by your own eyes.Not everything in FTD is perfect though, in fact one of the largest parts of the game can be quite buggy and frustrating - the combat. You can play the game with a controller or KB/M, but when playing with either I still encounter many enemies that I simply swing at them several times without actually hitting them, even when they're right in front of me. This can lead to some VERY frustrating experiences. On one of my own adventures I created I ran into a bug where it was impossible for me to kill an enemy, and eventually I ended up being pushed off of the map. Reading other reviews it seems I'm not the only one that has had problems with the combat.Aesthetically the game isn't astounding, but the landscapes can sometimes be very pleasing. The soundtrack again isn't amazing, but there are a decent selection of tracks - you can even choose which will play in your adventure. Even further you can set ""triggers"" that will cue a certain track when an event happens (the ACK is amazing)!After logging 50+ hours in the game, and trudging through the frustrating parts I do have to still give it a thumbs up. The developers do pay attention to the community and they try and fix bugs pretty quick. Hopefully they will be able to fix the combat eventually, then this game would be a masterpiece, but for now I have give it an 8/10.TL;DR Game is really good except for some frustrating combat experience. Creative minds will enjoy making adventures."
,Recommended,250560,14604449,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,tudor1,"Probably one of the most charming and innovative little games i have ever come across. Fight the Dragon allows it's players to develop an RPG style character while at the same time, building their own worlds/levels and even allowing you to share your own and play other people's levels. The artwork style is very very attractive and the game runs great. It will take anyone a little while to grasp some of the mechanics of the level builder but within the hour you'll be cruising along setting traps, spawning trolls and building towering castle walls. The building style is essentially Minecraft but with a blank canvas and on a much grander scale. Sadly however the community hasn't really kicked off as of yet so youre looking at only 1500 content creators. 9/10 and i hope this game gets more publicity."
