,Recommended,250560,18276429,"Posted: 1 October, 2015",all,Rabbit Sensei Gaming,"If you're looking at purchasing ""Fight the Dragon"", you are making a pretty wise investment with your funds.This title is a dungeon crawler, similar to the games like: ""Diablo"", but with a more light-hearted look and feel to it. However, there's a bit of a different twist to it. For, while you'll start off playing some basic developer created levels, to get aquainted with how the gameplay fully works, you'll soon find that the rest of the game is playing stages that other users have designed.This aspect, in itself, gives the game massive amounts of replayability. As there are new maps (and even campaigns!) being created, by people around the world, each and every day.But, sometimes, we don't want to play other people's levels. So, alongside the gameplay elements of this title, there is also a built-in level creator (Which you probably already guessed at, thanks to the above statements). And, my god is it a good one!The level creator gives you massive variety on what you can build with, and every tool that the developers used when making their stages as well. At first, it will feel a little overwhelming, as there are so many options to choose from, when looking at the blank canvas. However, the tools provided to you are so easy to learn that, as you practice (and play around) with them, you'll find yourself becoming more and more adept, and soon will be making stages that even the devlopers would be jealous of!All these good things said though, there are a few issues that I do have with the game.1 - The difficulty to this game is pretty low, once you get a single good weapon and piece of armor. Allowing you to solo ""Extreme"" difficulty stages, with little problem.2 - You can not fight the final boss (aka: the Dragon) in multi-player. Though, this was likely due to coding reasons, it still takes away a little bit from the feeling of an adventure, when most of the time, you're going to find yourself fighting through levels with your friends, or random allies.3 - The soundtrack isn't that varied, and is limited to maybe a total of 5 or 6 different tunes (Though, what little tracks there are, are still amazing).Despite these small issues I found with the game, ""Fight the Dragon"" is still an AMAZING game! One of which you'll find yourself putting many hours of your life into, just as I did when I played an almost non-stop 24 hour spree of the game.Yes. It's THAT addicting.Final Score: 8.5/10"
