,Recommended,250560,15238746,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,America Has A Problem #LasVegas,"Really an amazing experience, don't let the cartoon facade fool you. It's a bit like dark souls meets your-favorite-isometric-camera-arpg, with a built in map maker.The combat is what brings the game to bear similarity to dark souls (for me). You can dodge, roll, block and stun enemies with certain abilities. You then have selectable abilities that can enhance combat and really make your class shine, unlocking their true potential. It also feels relatively balanced and consistent in how it scales difficulties that gameplay never feels stagnant. Actually, gameplay feels quite rewarding. Upgrading stats or putting on new gear. You work hard for those first few rare pieces and it feels like a small accomplishment.The map maker is where the online portion of the game thrives; all players can make and submit their own unique creations using a very intuitive and simple development interface similar to voxel based construction games. You can set traps, create false doors, use movable objects to hide switches and levers, create npc's who trigger events, create anything and make it trigger an event, set up boss monsters and create pools of phat lewt; possibilities are endless. The magic comes in the creation of adventures (these are what the maps are effectively called in Fight the Dragon) and exploring other user's creations either solo or with friends. I'm about 6 hours into the game and have spent half of my time making my own mazes and arenas. It's addicting and fun.At under 10$ (I got this for 5$ on a steam sale), I would gladly pay full price for a title like this. If you are an arpg fan, or a dungeon maker fan of anykind..you must try to Fight the Dragon."
