,Recommended,250560,16270651,"Posted: 8 June, 2015",all,Batman Sucker Punch,"Fight the Dragon is a pretty charming game.  With four classes and countless player-made levels, it offers a lot of replayability.  After getting all four classes to level 60, I have still yet to ""Fight the Dragon"" more than a few times. And that's one of the great things about this game, you can really play it how you want. The level editor is shockingly good and in-depth. You can make anything from a simple arena with waves of mobs or recreate your favorite D&D scenario.  My first day I stumbled upon a recreation of Diablo III Act I, the story and all. It was amazing! You could really tell the creator spent a lot of time working on it, and it was damn fun.  I have quite a few favorites that I revisit because they are so well made.I was looking for a hack n slash style game with a light hearted feel and not so dark for a change. To be honest this fit the bill better than I could have ever imagined. Fight the Dragon was worth every cent of $15."
,Recommended,250560,16545661,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,shapes345,"pretty dank, pretty swank."
,Recommended,250560,16546376,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,PlasticLizard,"There is an indescribable charm about this game that I just can't get over. I picked it up during the Summer Sale because it was less than three bucks. My expectations going in were for an hour-or-two-throwaway, barely finished product.What I got instead has enthralled me so much the past two days. I can play for five minutes or get lost in a two-hour binge. The maps are long enough to feel detailed but short enough to complete in one sitting. Combat can get repetitive but with new and better loot dropping here and there, from enemies and chests, I didn't really care; it's good, plain fun. There are four classes with individual spells and special abilities - a fighter, fire mage, ice mage and rogue - but I've only played as an ""Ice Wizard"" up to this point without losing any interest or even gaining a desire to try other classes. I'm having too much fun with this one.There's also a map/adventure/campaign editor where you can create your own landscapes, buildings, villages, etc. etc. You can also script NPCs to talk to the player when he approaches as well as decorate your worlds with trees, rocks, fountains, bookshelves, beds, chairs... You name it. With a touch of detail here and there, worlds come alive. The editor has some rudimentary logic chains and pressure pads so that you can create some quite interesting and complex puzzles, though I'll admit, I haven't delved into that area quite yet.Buy this game. You will not regret it. I haven't had this much fun playing a game in who knows how long."
